\begin_layout Subsection
Orbit Equation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The radial equation used the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $l=$
\end_inset

constant to eliminate the angular dependence from the energy equation.
 The orbit equation uses the same principle, that 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 is constant, to eliminate time from the equation, to relate 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This gives the equation
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r\left(1-\epsilon\cos\theta\right)=r_{0}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{0}=\frac{l^{2}}{mk}$
\end_inset

 which is the radius that a circular orbit for the particular values of
 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 would have, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon=\sqrt{1+\frac{2El^{2}}{mk^{2}}}$
\end_inset

 which is the eccentricity and characterises the shape of the orbit.
 This is derived by starting with the equation in plane polars, then making
 the 2 substitutions,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
u & = & \frac{1}{r}\;\rightarrow\;\frac{\text{d}u}{\text{d}\theta}=-\frac{1}{r^{2}}\frac{\text{d}r}{\text{d}\theta}\\
\Rightarrow\dot{r} & = & \frac{\text{d}r}{\text{d}t}=\frac{\text{d}r}{\text{d}\theta}\dot{\theta}=-r^{2}\dot{\theta}\frac{\text{d}u}{\text{d}\theta}=-\frac{l}{m}\frac{\text{d}u}{\text{d}\theta}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
